Preheat your oven to 220°C/200°C fan/gas mark 7.

Chop the @potatoes{450%grams} lengthways into 1cm slices, then chop into 1cm
wide chips (no need to peel).

Pop the chips onto a large #baking tray{}. Drizzle with @olive oil{for the chips},
season with @salt{} and @ground black pepper{}, then toss to coat. Spread out in
a single layer.

TIP: Use two baking trays if necessary.

When the oven is hot, bake the chips on the middle shelf until golden, ~{30-35%minutes}.
Turn halfway through.

Lay the @British chicken breasts{2} onto another large baking tray, drizzle with
@olive oil{for the chicken} and half the @honey{7.5%grams}. Season with @salt{}
and @ground black pepper{}.

TIP: If your honey has hardened, pop it in a bowl of hot water for ~{1%minute}.

Sprinkle the @grated hard Italian style cheese{20%grams} on top of the chicken.

Roast on the top shelf of your oven until cooked through, ~{25-30%minutes}.

> IMPORTANT: Wash your hands and equipment after handling raw chicken and its
> packaging. It's cooked when no longer pink in the middle.

Meanwhile, roughly chop the @olives{30%grams} into small pieces.

In a #small bowl{}, combine the olives with the @sun-dried tomato paste{25%grams},
@chilli flakes{1%pinch} (add less if you'd prefer things milder), remaining
@honey{7.5%grams} and the @olive oil for the dressing{1.5%tbsp} and @water{1%tbsp}.
Season with @salt{} and @ground black pepper{}.

Transfer the cheesy chicken to your #plates{} and spoon over the puttanesca salsa.

Add the @baby leaf mix{50%grams} to the side and drizzle with the
@balsamic glaze{12%ml}.

Serve with chips and @mayonnaise{2%tbsp} alongside for dipping.

Enjoy!